Hollandaise Sauce
Yield: about 1 cup

Ingredients
	•	3 large egg yolks, room temperature
	•	1½ tbsp fresh lemon juice
	•	1 tbsp cold water
	•	3/4c unsalted butter
	•	Fine salt, to taste
	•	Very small pinch cayenne or white pepper (optional)

Before You Start
Hollandaise fails for two reasons: too much heat or adding butter too fast. Work gently. Everything should be warm, never hot.

Step 1 — Clarify the Butter
Melt the butter over low heat without stirring.
Skim off the white foam.
Slowly pour the clear yellow butter into a heatproof cup, leaving the milky solids behind.
Keep the clarified butter warm.

Step 2 — Make the Egg Base
In a metal or heatproof bowl, whisk together:
	•	egg yolks
	•	lemon juice
	•	water

Whisk until completely smooth.

Step 3 — Thicken the Eggs (Critical Step)
Place the bowl over a pot of gently simmering water. The bowl must not touch the water.

Whisk constantly for 1–2 minutes. The mixture should:
	•	thicken noticeably
	•	turn pale
	•	form soft ribbons when the whisk is lifted

Remove from heat immediately once this stage is reached. Grainy texture means overcooked.

Step 4 — Emulsify with Butter
While whisking constantly, add the warm clarified butter very slowly.
Start with a few drops, then a thin steady stream.

The sauce should:
	•	thicken smoothly
	•	look glossy
	•	stay fully emulsified with no oil separation

If it becomes too thick, whisk in 1 tsp warm water to loosen.

Step 5 — Season
Season with fine salt to taste.
Add a very small pinch of cayenne or white pepper if desired.
Adjust lemon only at the end, a few drops at a time.

Finished Texture
Smooth, pale yellow, glossy. Thick enough to coat a spoon. Never greasy or oily.

Holding
Keep warm, not hot (about hot tap-water temperature).
Do not refrigerate.
Use within 30–45 minutes.

If the Sauce Breaks
In a clean bowl, whisk 1 tsp warm water.
Slowly whisk the broken sauce into it until smooth again.